[qui cum matre 9] These words (omitted from the text) are very probably an adscript, or rather the remains of an adscript. There is no further reference to Sassia, and Cicero goes on at once to speak of reus et accusator, which connects immediately with cum Oppianico Cluentius. Sassia’s relentless hatred might well occur to a copyist (if not to the speaker himself at this point), as an obstacle to the reconciliation of Cluentius with Oppianicus.
